RUN DESIGN
Possibly a Hero | Canonical Run Mechanics Specification
STATUS: Draft

---

1. FOUNDATIONAL CONTEXT

Possibly a Hero is two games fused into one. The run is the action half. The
city is the consequence half. Neither functions without the other — not
thematically, not mechanically, not in how the player understands what they're
doing or why it matters.

Runs generate three types of output: resources, morale, and intel. These flow
into the city layer after every run, successful or not. The city reflects and
deepens what the player has done across those runs. It does not control what
the player can access in runs. City buildings are mirrors, not doors.

The full hero power pool is available from run one. No city building holds a
power back from appearing. No construction project unlocks a combo. Players
enter each run with their class and their starting offensive power. Everything
else gets built during the run, from a pool that was never gated.

What the city does is remember. It shows the player what they've built, what
they've survived, and who the world has decided they're becoming. The run is
where the story happens. The city is where the story lives.

Any system treating these as separate modes has misread the game.

---

2. RUN INITIATION

Every run begins before the map loads. The choices made in the pre-run menu
are the ones the cinematic pays off.

Sequence:
1. Player selects class. Four options: Brawler, Speedster, Blaster, Tactician.
2. Player selects starting offensive power — only if more than one has been
   unlocked for that class. Single-unlock players skip this step entirely.
3. Map loads.
4. Intro scene plays. Third-person, brief, cinematic. The hero arrives in
   the city via their class movement type.
5. Camera transitions to isometric offset play mode.
6. Run begins.

The camera transition is the payoff of class selection — not a separate
mechanical choice, not a consequence of movement power selection. The hero
arrives the way they arrive because of who they are. The class was chosen
before the map loaded. The intro is the world acknowledging that choice.

Class intro animations:

- Brawler: Leaps into frame. Lands hard enough to crack the ground. Camera
  swings up to isometric.
- Speedster: Blurs in from off-screen. Camera snaps up with motion blur still
  resolving around the hero.
- Blaster: Teleports in. Hard cut to isometric — no drift, no settle, no
  transition. Just suddenly there.
- Tactician: Rolls in on vehicle. Camera lifts steadily and settles with the
  deliberateness of someone who planned the approach.

Each animation communicates class identity before a single enemy appears. The
Brawler hits the ground. The Speedster was already there. The Blaster arrives
without warning. The Tactician arrives with infrastructure. Third-person assets
are scoped exclusively to this intro sequence. The isometric offset angle
handles all run gameplay from the moment the camera settles.

---

3. CAMERA AND PERSPECTIVE

The camera model is Hades — closer and more angled than Deep Rock Galactic
Survivors. DRGS is retired as a reference for this game. It described the
wrong thing.

At Hades distance, individual enemies have presence. Movement types read as
identity rather than speed statistics. A heavy enemy that telegraphs a charge
plays differently from a fast enemy that flanks — and the player can read that
difference because the camera lets them see it. Bodies on the ground look like
bodies. A power landing on a cluster of enemies reads as impact, not as a
number increasing.

The city at this distance feels like a place. Storefronts. Alleyways.
Recognizable buildings that exist in both the run layer and the city layer.
The same street corner the player has rebuilt looks like that street corner
when they're running through it. Not a map. Not a level. A city the player
helped build, and is now fighting through.

Camera scope:
- Third-person perspective: intro sequence only
- Isometric offset: all run gameplay
- Third-person asset investment is bounded by the intro sequence scope

Reference hierarchy:
- Run camera and combat feel: Hades
- Run structure and loop: Vampire Survivors
- DRGS: retired

