7. RUN TIME STRUCTURE — THREE ACTS

A run targets twenty minutes. Every run has the same shape — not a hard
mechanical clock, but a design target that a well-executed run naturally
follows. The map, the mission locations, and the build are different every
time. The shape is not.

ACT ONE — PREP PERIOD (0:00 – 5:00)

Mission locations are hidden. The player does not know where the Boss Fight,
the Escort Defense, or the Horde Survival will be. They know all three exist
somewhere on the map. They don't know where.

The player moves through the city freely, leveling up through milestone-based
power selections. Minor objectives are live. The build is forming. The city
is already reacting to the fact that someone is out there.

Stumbling into a mission location before the prep period ends makes that
mission live immediately. The map does not protect the player from finding it
early. The mission does not wait for the five-minute mark. A player who blunders
into a horde zone at minute two with two powers and a support is going to find
out what those two powers and a support can do under pressure. This is not a
punishment. This is how the city keeps the run from feeling like a menu with
a countdown.

ACT TWO — OPEN WINDOW (5:00 – 15:00)

At the five-minute mark, all three mission locations reveal simultaneously on
the map. Full information. Full agency. The player now knows exactly where
everything is.

They can attempt a mission immediately with whatever they've built. They can
keep developing the loadout and hold the decision. They can hit a minor
objective on the way across the map to a mission they're not sure they're
ready for. There is no mechanical penalty for waiting. There is no mechanical
bonus for rushing. The Open Window is ten minutes of genuine player choice —
the longest sustained period of player agency in the run.

ACT THREE — FORCED COMMITMENT (15:00 onward)

At the fifteen-minute mark, the window closes. The game forces a mission
choice. Whatever the player built across the first fifteen minutes is the build
going in. Loadout development stops. Failure to commit results in run failure.

The forced commitment is the run's dramatic spine. Every milestone choice,
every minor objective taken or passed, every second spent developing versus
rotating — it lands here. The build meets the mission. A prepared player
resolves the mission in approximately five minutes. There is no hard timer on
the mission itself — the twenty-minute figure is the natural rhythm of a
well-executed run, not a death clock. Success or failure resolves in Act Three.

---

8. RUN RESOLUTION

Every run resolves with outputs that feed the city layer and the player's
permanent currency.

Successful run: Generates resources, morale, or intel depending on mission
type completed. City development advances. Hero Points accumulate from mob
drops and minor objectives completed during the run — full carry, no reduction.
The mirror gets brighter.

Failed or abandoned run: Atmospheric consequence only. No progress is reversed.
No construction is undone. No city building disappears. Hero Points earned
during the run carry forward in full — what the player earned while the run
lasted is theirs permanently. The city absorbs the loss without surrendering
it. The player returns to a city that knows things went badly, not a city
that was set back.

Run patterns accumulate. A streak of bad runs darkens the city over a short
window — citizens pull indoors, visual tone shifts, Rex Flynn has opinions he
broadcasts at volume. None of it is permanent. The city recovers. The hero
goes again. The story keeps writing itself, one run at a time, whether the
last run was the best one or the worst one in the record.

